PREFACE
	The present <I>Index</I> was begun in 1918, while Mr. Arthur Stanley Pease was still a member of the Department of Classics at the University of Illinois, and it is to be regretted that his connexion with the enterprise was severed so soon after its planning and inception.
	The preliminary collections of material were made by a number of graduate students in partial fulfilment of the requirements for the Master's Degree. At a later time it was made possible, through the generosity of Dean A. H. Daniels, of the Graduate School of the University of Illinois, to secure the aid of two or three more advanced scholars in the labors of composition and verification. The names of all those who have assisted us in this way follow, and we wish to express herewith our sincere gratitude for their generous and devoted assistance.
	K. M. Abbott (verification); Hazel M. Bowlus (Mrs. C. E. Moore) (collection); L. W. Daly (verification); C. E. Finch (arrangement and verification); C. A. Forbes (verification); Leola G. Harding (collection); L. D. Johnston (verification); Helen L. Jones (collection); Edna M. Killough (collection); L. R. Lind (verification); Mildred M. Madden (collection); Erva M. Moody (collection); Mary Helen Orton (Mrs. Lawrence E. Clark) (collection); Ora Rush (collection); K. F. Vickery (composition).
	We venture to call our compilation a "critical index," because we have endeavored to indicate by appropriate sigla those cases in which any possible doubt might exist regarding the authenticity of any particular form or spelling. Every citation of a word upon which there is some statement in the <I>apparatus criticus</I> is enclosed in ( ). Every citation of a word which appears only in the <I>apparatus criticus</I> is enclosed in [ ]. Every citation of a word which, although left in the text, has a &dagger; prefixed to it, is marked thus (&dagger;). Citations of all the new critical material are enclosed in &lobrk; &robrk;. An asterisk (<SUP>*</SUP>) is attached to every citation of a word or form about which some statement may be found in the <I>Additamentum ad Apparatum Criticum.</I> It is hoped that in this way a fairly reliable conspectus may be afforded of the authority back of each word or form cited, as such authority is known at the present stage of textual criticism.
	After the materials had been collected on cards, and upon consultation with Messrs. Rudolf Helm, D. S. Robertson, and Paul Vallette, who courteously advised with us upon this matter, it was decided to add to the book and chapter references the line in the Teubner text of that chapter in which each citation occurred. This extremely laborious task was in the main performed by Mr. H. V. Canter, and to his conscientious accuracy in that matter all who use this work will be permanently indebted.
	In the <I>Metamorphoses,</I> where the chapters are seldom more than 30 lines in length, one might have managed to get along with only chapter references, but with chapters of 60 and 70 lines, as in the <I>&pi;&epsilon;&rho;&iotagrave; &epsilq;&rho;&mu;&eta;&nu;&epsilon;&iotaacute;&alpha;&sigmav;,</I> to say nothing of the <I>Florida,</I> where several of the chapters exceed 100 lines in length, no one could fairly be expected to look over two or more entire pages in search of a single word. The reference to chapter-line in a standard edition was preferred, because it involves far fewer numbers than would a reference to page and line of Oudendorp's edition, and because the standard text series (Teubner, Oxford, Bud&eacute;, and Paravia) have almost the same number of ems per line, so that up to about ten lines the correspondence is very close, when not exact, while even with higher numbers one quickly learns to add or subtract a fraction of a line for each multiple of ten.<SUP>1</SUP> And in any event, even without very close correspondence, much time will be saved by knowing in approximately what part of the chapter to start looking.
	The arrangement of inflected words is that of the paradigms in the ordinary grammars, following the usage adopted for the <I>Index to Seneca's Tragedies</I> (<I>University of Illinois Studies in Language and Literature,</I> Vol. IV, 1918), and this system has saved thousands of explanatory notes. The first citation is understood to be that of the entry form; if there are different genders, the first citation is the masculine, without further statement.
	Readings for which no reasonable syntax or sense could easily be imagined have been grouped at the end of the article to which they seem to belong. Perhaps more readings should have been thus classified, and no doubt a few thus listed belong in the body of the article, but it has been difficult to be quite consistent upon this point. Likewise <I>voces nihili</I> are ordinarily listed separately even when it is fairly clear what they were intended to represent. When, however, the variant is quite certainly intended for a recognized form, and the spelling employed is merely a mediaeval way of writing that same form, the variant has gen-
***
	<SUP>1</SUP> In this connexion editors of prose texts are respectfully urged to divide up chapters or sections into very small units, like the verses of the Bible, for convenience of reference. These might normally be complete sentences, except where such exceed approximately five lines in length, when any clearly recognizable pause might be used. The reference then to such a small subdivision would be sufficient. Of course, later editors might punctuate a little differently, but there could be no harm in retaining such previous 'verse' numbers as had once been listed in an index, or had got into the critical literature, and even at the worst the variation between different editions in the total number of sentences in a section or chapter could never be very great.
	A modest protest might also be filed against the use of Roman numerals wherever Arabic will suffice, and especially against such confusing ones as IIII and VIIII for 4 and 9, no matter what the technical justification for these may be. The innumerable errors which they inevitably cause, even when one is especially on one's guard against them, and the scores of hours wasted in correcting the same, constitute all the argument needed.
***
erally been listed in its proper place in the body of an article, although here again complete consistency may not always have been maintained.
In a few instances double entries have been made, where one classification appeared to be about as reasonable as another. This practice may be justified if it renders a form easier to find. After all, our purpose has been, not so much to classify the grammatical usages of Apuleius, as to make it relatively easy to find any particular form desired, and to identify rapidly references and citations. The grammatical classification will, no doubt, often be faulty, but if all the occurrences of each word are actually listed, we shall have attained our chief aim. If there is danger of confusing different forms because of similarity in spelling, it might be well for the user of this index to consult the other similar spellings in order to make sure that no instance is being overlooked, since we cannot guarantee the correctness of all our classifications. The verification of references must always remain part of the duty of scholars, and a work of this kind, even at the best, should be an aid rather than a substitute.
In regard to the mistakes which probably remain in considerable numbers, even after much checking and verification, it might be pointed out that in addition to the ordinary errors of misunderstanding, and the clerical and typographical slips involved in writing, copying, and printing, a work of this kind is subject to a few special kinds of oversights. For example, when several instances of the same form are listed on the same card, the collector may know perfectly well that <I>illo,</I> for instance, is masculine and not neuter, but by accident may pick up the card containing the neuters instead of the masculines, and thus make a false entry. Again, in verification, a neighboring form with the same spelling may catch the eye, and an erroneous classification result. Once more, in entering the several thousand words which for one reason or another failed to be included in the first draft,<SUP>2</SUP> a considerable number of merely clerical errors have resulted, in addition to the mistakes made in understanding the implications of the necessarily condensed records of the <I>apparatus criticus.</I> All the original classifications were verified in our manuscript by reference to the text again, where the word was underscored. Since, however, it would happen, perhaps once or twice for each page, that a word (or even an entire line) was skipped in the verification, there doubtless remain cases where an originally false entry still stands,
***
<SUP>2</SUP> About 3 per cent of all the readings in the original text escaped record in the first draft and had to be entered later. Another 1 per cent, approximately, represent new matter. Thus some 4 per cent of our total text (or upwards of 5,000 entries all told) represent additions made to the original manuscript, and unless a person has actually caught himself over and over again starting to put an entry in the wrong place, he has no real appreciation of how easy it is to make a mistake in such a relatively simple matter. Especially treacherous is the tendency, in citing some reading from the <I>apparatus criticus,</I> to give the line for that according to the page of the Teubner text, by which it is listed in the <I>apparatus,</I> rather than by the line of the chapter.
***
because the word was not verified and underscored in the text, and when entered later was put in the correct place.
In general it may be remarked that any quite consistent application of even a sound principle will lead occasionally to absurdities, or at least superfluities, but we have preferred to err on the side of consistency, if at all. Yet consistency is a delicate matter, and in the many intricate, if not particularly important details which a work like this involves, it would be difficult enough for even a single individual to be consistent throughout, and quite impossible for a group of half a dozen or more. We only hope such irregularities will not greatly inconvenience the users of our work.
A new collection of the fragments, since they were not included in the Teubner text, has been prepared by Mr. Perry, and will be found at the end of this preface.
In the preparation of the <I>Index</I> we have followed the texts of R. Helm for the <I>Metamorphoses</I> (2nd ed. 1913), <I>Apologia</I> (2nd ed. 1912), and <I>Florida</I> (1910), and that of P. Thomas for the philosophical works (1908). Much water has, of course, run under the mill since those dates, and we have felt it desirable, therefore, to collect the new critical material which has accumulated in the interval, and, by entering it with the appropriate sigla, to bring the <I>Index,</I> as best we can, down to date.
<SCAP>William Abbott Oldfather
Howard Vernon Canter
Ben Edwin Perry</SCAP>
17 July, 1933
Urbana, Illinois

	23. <I>Idem, de Ostentis 4</I> (<I>ed. Wachsmuth</I>)<I>:</I> &rsquo;&Alpha;<I>&pi;&omicron;&upsi;&lambda;&etaacute;&iotauml;&omicron;&sigmav; &delta;&epsigrave; &pi;&epsilon;&rho;&iotagrave; &tau;&omegacirc;&nu; &tau;&omicron;&iota;&upsiacute;&tau;&omega;&nu; &gamma;&rho;&alphaacute;&phi;&omega;&nu; &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave; &upsilq;&pi;&omicrgrave;</I> <U>&Kappa;</U><I><U>&lambda;&alpha;&upsi;&delta;&iotaacute;&omegaogonek;</U></I> <U>&Kappa;</U><I><U>&alpha;&iotaacute;&sigma;&alpha;&rho;&iota; &tau;&rho;&epsilon;&iotacirc;&sigmav; &epsilq;&lambda;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;&sigmav;</U> &omicrrq;&phi;&theta;&etacirc;&nu;&alpha;&iotaacute; &phi;&eta;&sigma;&iota;&nu;, &omicrlq;&mu;&omicron;&iotaacute;&omega;&sigmav; &delta;&epsigrave; &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave; <U>&sigma;&epsilon;&lambda;&etaacute;&nu;&alpha;&sigmav;</U> &tau;&omicron;&sigmav;&alpha;&upsiacute;&tau;&alpha;&sigmav; &epsirq;&pi;&iotagrave;</I> <U>&Gamma;</U><I><U>&alpha;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;</U></I> <U>&rsquo;&Alpha;</U><I><U>&nu;&nu;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;</U> &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave;</I> &lt;<U>&Gamma;<I>&nu;&alpha;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;</U></I><U>&gt; &Delta;</U><I><U>&omicron;&mu;&iota;&tau;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;</U> &tau;&omegacirc;&nu; &upsilq;&pi;&alphaacute;&tau;&omega;&nu;&middot; &lt;&omegalqcircogonek;&gt; &alpharqacute;&nu;&tau;&iota;&kappa;&rho;&upsi;&sigmav; &epsirq;&delta;&eta;&lambda;&omicron;&upsicirc;&tau;&omicron;</I> <U>&Gamma;</U><I><U>&alphaacute;&lambda;&lambda;&omicron;&upsi;&sigmav;</U> &tau;&epsilon; &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave;</I> <U>&Sigma;</U><I><U>&alpha;&upsi;&rho;&omicron;&mu;&alphaacute;&tau;&alpha;&sigmav;</U> &tau;&alphagrave;</I> '&Rho;<I>&omega;&mu;&alpha;&iotaacute;&omega;&nu; &delta;&etaogonek;&omegaacute;&sigma;&epsilon;&iota;&nu;.</I>
	&Gamma;<I>&alpha;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;</I> &rsquo;&Alpha;<I>&nu;&nu;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi; &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave;</I> &Gamma;<I>&nu;&alpha;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;</I> &Delta;<I>&omicron;&mu;&iota;&tau;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi; scripsit Wachsmuth pro</I> &Gamma;<I>&nu;&alpha;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi; &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave;</I> &Delta;<I>&omicron;&mu;&iota;&tau;&iotaacute;&omicron;&upsi;, nixus Plinii librorum scriptura,</I> <SCAP>ii,</SCAP> 99: lunae quoque trinae, ut Cn. 	24. <I>Ibid.</I> 7: <I>&tau;&alpha;&upsirq;&tau;&omicrgrave; &delta;&epsigrave; &tau;&omicron;&upsicirc;&tau;&omicron;</I> (<I>sc. saxum de caelo in terram missum</I>) <I>&kappa;&alpha;&tau;&alphaacute; &tau;&epsilon;</I> &rsquo;&acute;<U>&Alpha;</U><I><U>&beta;&upsi;&delta;&omicron;&nu;</U> &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave;</I> <U>&Kappa;</U><I><U>&upsiacute;&zeta;&iota;&kappa;&omicron;&nu;</U> &sigma;&upsi;&mu;&beta;&etacirc;&nu;&alpha;&iotaacute; &phi;&eta;&sigma;&iota;&nu;</I> &rsquo;&Alpha;<I>&pi;&omicron;&upsi;&lambda;&etaacute;&iotauml;&omicron;&sigmav;&middot; &omicrlqacute;&theta;&epsilon;&nu; &epsirqacute;&tau;&iota; &kappa;&alpha;&iotaacute; &nu;&upsicirc;&nu; &lambda;&iotaacute;&theta;&omicron;&sigmav; &epsirq;&sigma;&tau;&iotagrave; &pi;&alpha;&rho;' &alpha;&upsirq;&tau;&omicron;&iotacirc;&sigmav; &pi;&upsi;&rho;&omegaacute;&delta;&eta;&sigmav; &mu;&epsigrave;&nu; &tau;&omicrgrave; &chi;&rho;&omegacirc;&mu;&alpha;, &sigma;&iota;&delta;&etaacute;&rho;&omegaogonek; &delta;&epsigrave; &alphalqacute;&pi;&alpha;&sigmav; &kappa;&alpha;&tau;&alpha;&sigma;&epsilon;&sigma;&eta;&mu;&alpha;&sigma;&mu;&epsirq;&nu;&omicron;&sigmav;&middot; &pi;&alpha;&rho;&alpha;&delta;&epsilon;&delta;&omicracute;&sigma;&theta;&alpha;&iota; &gamma;&alphagrave;&rho; &lambda;&omicracute;&gamma;&omicron;&sigmav;</I> <U>&Kappa;</U><I><U>&upsi;&zeta;&iota;&kappa;&eta;&nu;&omicron;&iotacirc;&sigmav;</U> &omegalq;&sigmav; &sigma;&upsi;&nu;&alpha;&pi;&omicron;&lambda;&epsiacute;&sigma;&alpha;&iota; &tau;&omegaogonekcirc; &lambda;&iotaacute;&theta;&omegaogonek; &tau;&etagrave;&nu; &pi;&omicracute;&lambda;&iota;&nu; &alpharq;&nu;&alphaacute;&gamma;&kappa;&eta;.</I>
	25. <I>Ibid.</I> 44: <I>&kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave; &tau;&omicrgrave; &tau;&omicrgrave; &delta;&etagrave; &pi;&alphaacute;&nu;&tau;&omega;&nu; &theta;&alpha;&upsi;&mu;&alpha;&sigma;&iota;&omegaacute;&tau;&alpha;&tau;&omicron;&nu;, &epsirq;&pi;&iotagrave; &gamma;&upsi;&nu;&alpha;&iota;&kappa;&omicrgrave;&sigmav; &epsirq;&gamma;&kappa;&upsiacute;&mu;&omicron;&nu;&omicron;&sigmav; &sigma;&upsi;&mu;&beta;&etacirc;&nu;&alpha;&iotaacute; &phi;&eta;&sigma;&iota;&nu; &omicrlq; &mu;&epsiacute;&gamma;&alpha;&sigmav;</I> &rsquo;&Alpha;<I>&pi;&omicron;&upsi;&lambda;&etaacute;&iotauml;&omicron;&sigmav;, &kappa;&alpha;&iotagrave; &gamma;&upsi;&nu;&alpha;&iota;&kappa;&omicrgrave;&sigmav; &omicron;&upsirq;&kappa; &etarq;&gamma;&nu;&omicron;&eta;&mu;&epsiacute;&nu;&eta;&sigmav;,</I> <U>&Mu;</U><I><U>&alpha;&rho;&kappa;&iotaacute;&alpha;&sigmav;</U> &delta;&etagrave; &epsirq;&kappa;&epsi;&iotaacute;&nu;&eta;&sigma; &tau;&etacirc;&sigmav;</I> <U>&Kappa;<I>&alphaacute;&tau;&omega;&nu;&iota;</U> &tau;&omegaogonekcirc; &tau;&epsilon;&lambda;&epsilon;&upsi;&tau;&alpha;&iotaacute;&omegaogonek; &sigma;&upsi;&nu;&omicron;&iota;&kappa;&eta;&sigma;&alphaacute;&sigma;&eta;&sigmav;. &epsirq;&mu;&pi;&epsilon;&sigma;&omegagrave;&nu; &gamma;&alphagrave;&rho; &alpha;&upsirq;&tau;&etaogonekcirc; &kappa;&epsilon;&rho;&alpha;&upsi;&nu;&omicrgrave;&sigmav; &omicrlq; &lambda;&epsilon;&gamma;&omicracute;&mu;&epsilon;&nu;&omicron;&sigmav; &alpharq;&rho;&gamma;&etagrave;&sigmav; &etarqacute;&tau;&omicron;&iota; &lambda;&alpha;&mu;&pi;&rho;&omicrgrave;&sigmav; &alpha;&upsirq;&tau;&etagrave;&nu; &mu;&epsigrave;&nu; &pi;&alpha;&nu;&tau;&epsilon;&lambda;&omegacirc;&sigmav; &epsilonrq;&phi;&upsiacute;&lambda;&alpha;&xi;&epsilon;&nu; &alpharq;&beta;&lambda;&alpha;&beta;&etacirc;, &kappa;&tau;&lambda;.</I>
ANEXOMENO&Sigma;
<I>Baehrens, P.L.M. IV, 104 sq.</I>
L. APULEI ex Menandro
Amare liceat, si potiri non licet.
Fruantur alii: non moror, non sum inuidus;
Nam sese excruciat, qui beatis inuidet.
Quos Venus amauit, facit amoris compotes:
5 Nobis Cupido uelle dat, posse abnegat.
Olli purpurea delibantes oscula
Demente morsu rosea labia uellicent,
Candentes dentes effigient suauio,
Malas adorent ore et ingenuas genas
10 Et pupularum nitidas geminas gemmulas.
Quin et cum tenera membra molli lectulo
Consertiora adhaerent Veneris glutino,
Libido cum lasciua instinctos suscitat
Sinuare ad Veneris cursum femina feminae:
15 Inter gannitus et subantis uoculas
Carpant papillas atque amplexus intiment
Reserentque sulcos molles aruo Venerio
Thyrsumque pangant hortulo Cupidinis,
Dent crebros ictus coniuente lumine,
20 Trepidante e cursu uena et anima fessula
Eiaculent tepidum rorem niueis laticibus.
Haec illi faciant, queis Venus non inuidet;
At nobis casso saltem delectamine
Amare liceat, si potiri non licet!
	<I>114</I> (<I>B. III 231, M. 230</I>). <I>cf. quae disputavi Mus. Rhen. XXXI, 262 sqq.</I> &par; <I>4</I> fecit <I>S, corr. Binetus</I> &par; 7 Demente <I>scripsi:</I> Clemente <I>W</I> &pipe; labia (<I>uel</I> labra) <I>Riesius:</I> labella <I>W</I> &par; <I>8 om. Binetus, sed 'agnoscit teste Sauarone ad Sidonium Cl. Bineti MS. schedium'</I> &pipe; effugient <I>W</I> &par; <I>9</I> odorent <I>W, corr. Scriuerius</I> &par; <I>12</I> Consertiora <I>scripsi:</I> Cum pectora <I>W</I> (<I>post</I> pectora <I>Binetus</I> una, <I>Dousa</I> arte <I>addunt</I>) Compectorata <I>Scriuerius</I> Compaginata <I>Buechelerus</I> Complexiora <I>Riesius</I> &par; <I>13</I> lasciuia instincto <I>W, correxi;</I> lasciuo instinctu <I>Binetus</I> lasciua instricta <I>Coluius</I> &pipe; suscitet <I>W, corr. Coluius</I> &par; <I>14</I> Sinuent <I>Binetus</I> &pipe; at ueneri cursum <I>W, corr. Binetus</I> (usum <I>Scriuerius</I>) &pipe; foemine <I>W</I> &par; <I>17</I> Reserentque <I>scripsi:</I> Haerentque <I>W</I> Iterentque <I>uel</I> Arentque <I>Binetus</I> &par; <I>18</I> hortulo <I>Binetus:</I> horto in <I>W</I> &par; <I>19</I> Dent <I>Binetus:</I> Dum <I>W</I> &pipe; conniuente <I>idem:</I> conhibente <I>W</I> conbibente <I>Dousa</I> &par; <I>20</I> Crepidante <I>W, corr. Binetus</I> &pipe; e <I>addidi: om. W</I> &pipe; uena <I>scripsi:</I> Venere <I>W</I> &par; <I>21</I> lactibus <I>Binetus</I> &par; <I>23</I> esto <I>Meinekius.</I>
<I>ADDITAMENTVM AD APPARATVM CRITICVM</I>
	<I>Coniecturas atque novas codicum lectiones observationesque criticas, cum eas quas ad opera philosophica post Thomasium</I> (<I>a. 1908</I>) <I>ad</I> Apologiam <I>post Butlerum</I> (<I>1914</I>) <I>ad</I> Florida <I>post Helmium</I> (<I>1910</I>) <I>ad</I> Metamorphoseon <I>libros post Giarratanum</I> (<I>1929</I>) <I>publici iuris fecerunt viri docti, turn etiam eas, sive veteres ab Helmio praetermissas sive recentiores, quarum mentionem fecerunt in</I> Metamorphosibus <I>edendis Giarratano et in</I> Apologia <I>Butler, omnes fere hic infra in unum congestas subiunximus.</I>
<I>	Sequitur index virorum doctorum quorum commentationes ipsi excussimus. Nam multa et nomina auctorum et commentationes, quae in addilamento nostro laudantur, hic non leguntur, sed plerumque invenias aut apud Giarratanum aut Helmium aut Butlerum.</I>

[ ] uoces includunt quae sic in textu ipso designantur, uel solum in apparatu critico reperiuntur.
( ) uoces includunt quae et in textu ipso reperiuntur et aliqua de grauiore causa in apparatu critico commemorantur.
(&dagger;) uoces includunt quae siglo &dagger; in textu ipso designantur.
&lobrk; &robrk; uoces includunt quae solum in <I>Additamento ad Apparatum Criticum</I> reperiuntur.
<SUP>*</SUP> uoces designat de quibus consulendum est <I>Additamentum ad Apparatum Criticum.</I>

INDEX VOCVM GRAECARVM
<il><I>Nugas monstraque omnia proferre quae pro uocibus Graecis in codicibus Latinis recentioribus plerumque reperiuntur non operae pretium uisum est.</I></il>
<il>A (<I>litt. tantum</I>) H 13, 3; 13, 4; 13, 7.</il>
